---
import ServiceLayout from '../../layouts/ServiceLayout.astro';

const title = 'Booking &amp; reservation app development';
const description =
  'Booking apps for restaurants, salons, hotels, fitness studios and clinics. Calendars, slots, payments, reminders and recurring reservations — built for both iPhone and Android.';
---

<ServiceLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  serviceType="Booking and reservation mobile app development"
  breadcrumbs={[
    { href: '/', label: 'Home' },
    { href: '/apps', label: 'Mobile apps' },
    { href: '/apps/booking', label: 'Booking &amp; reservation' },
  ]}
>
  <p>
    Booking apps are deceptively simple. Show available slots, let someone book one, send a
    reminder, take payment. The complexity arrives the moment a real business uses it: staff
    schedules, multiple locations, services with different durations, deposits, cancellation
    policies, recurring appointments, group bookings, no-show fees, integrations with the
    calendar the business actually runs on. We build booking apps with all of those in mind,
    so the operator's daily life is genuinely easier than the spreadsheet they're replacing.
  </p>

  <h2>What we build</h2>
  <p>
    Restaurant reservations (with deposits, party size, special requests, integration with the
    kitchen's POS). Hair and beauty bookings (per-stylist availability, service durations,
    add-ons, walk-in support). Hotel and short-let bookings (calendar with seasonal pricing,
    deposits, channel manager integration). Fitness class and personal training bookings (group
    classes with capacity, cancellation cutoffs, packages of credits, recurring weekly
    bookings). Medical and clinical appointments (with intake forms, GDPR-compliant data
    handling, NHS or private). Equipment and resource bookings (meeting rooms, gym courts,
    studios). The patterns repeat; the details vary.
  </p>

  <h2>End-to-end work</h2>

  <h3>The calendar (the engine)</h3>
  <p>
    Underneath every booking app is a calendar engine that has to answer "is this slot
    available?" instantly, accounting for staff availability, room capacity, service duration,
    buffers between appointments, lead time, advance booking limits, recurring blocks, holidays,
    and time zones. Done badly, this is the part that makes the app slow or wrong. We build it
    properly using a tested availability algorithm and cache the results carefully so a busy
    booking screen doesn't hammer your database.
  </p>

  <h3>Customer-facing booking flow</h3>
  <p>
    Browse services, pick a date, see available slots, pick one, log in or sign up if needed,
    optionally pay a deposit, confirm. We design this to be possible in under a minute, with
    progressive disclosure (extra fields shown only when needed). For repeat customers, "book
    the usual" should be one tap. Apple Pay and Google Pay for deposits to keep checkout
    friction low.
  </p>

  <h3>Operator (business) app or web dashboard</h3>
  <p>
    The operator side is where booking apps make or break their value. We build either a
    second app or a responsive web dashboard depending on how the business actually works
    (front-of-house staff often prefer a tablet web view, mobile owners prefer an app). It
    needs: a daily/weekly calendar view that's quick to glance at, drag-to-reschedule, blocking
    out slots, walk-ins, no-show marking, deposit refunds, customer notes. We build it from
    real-world operator workflows, not abstractions.
  </p>

  <h3>Notifications and reminders</h3>
  <p>
    Confirmation immediately. Reminder twenty-four hours before. Reminder two hours before
    (catches the morning-of-day customers). Push, email, SMS — configurable per customer.
    Cancellation deadline reminders. Re-booking suggestions for regular customers. We tune the
    notification mix so it's helpful, not nagging.
  </p>

  <h3>Payments, deposits and cancellation policies</h3>
  <p>
    Stripe for card payments. Deposits at booking time (refundable per policy). No-show fees
    charged automatically per the policy you set (with proper card-on-file handling). Tipping
    where appropriate. Discount codes and gift vouchers. Recurring billing for membership
    packages (e.g., 10-class fitness packs, monthly memberships). Refunds initiated by the
    operator with audit trail.
  </p>

  <h3>Recurring and group bookings</h3>
  <p>
    Weekly classes that customers can book one-off, in a series, or via a recurring
    subscription. Group bookings (a party of six in a restaurant; a class of twelve in a
    yoga studio) with capacity tracking and waitlists. Family or team accounts where one
    person books for several. These features sound niche but they're often the deal-breaker
    that makes or kills adoption.
  </p>

  <h3>Integrations with existing tools</h3>
  <p>
    Sync with Google Calendar, Outlook, iCloud — so the operator's existing calendar shows
    bookings without manual data entry. Two-way sync to keep external blocks reflected. POS
    integrations for restaurants (Square, Lightspeed). Channel manager integration for short-let
    rentals (Booking.com, Airbnb via channel managers like Hostaway). Accounting integrations
    (Xero, QuickBooks) for end-of-month reconciliation.
  </p>

  <h3>GDPR, intake forms and data handling</h3>
  <p>
    For medical, beauty, and clinical bookings, intake forms collect health information that
    has to be stored properly. We build encrypted-at-rest storage, GDPR-compliant data
    retention and deletion, audit logs for who accessed what. For everyone: cookie consent,
    right to export and delete data, marketing-consent separated from booking-consent.
  </p>

  <h2>Pricing model</h2>
  <p>
    Booking apps work well as SaaS — operators pay you a monthly fee, you take a small cut
    of bookings, or both. We design the billing to match how the operators in your category
    think (per-location, per-staff-seat, per-booking, flat-rate). Multi-tenancy is baked in
    from day one so you can onboard one operator or a thousand without re-architecting.
  </p>

  <h2>What it costs</h2>
  <p>
    A booking app for a single business (one location, single platform) starts at £15,000.
    A multi-tenant SaaS booking platform serving multiple operators starts at £35,000 and
    scales up with the integrations and complexity of the operator dashboard. Hosting, SMS
    fees (Twilio or similar), and Stripe processing fees are billed to you directly.
  </p>

  <h2>Timeline</h2>
  <p>
    Single-business booking app: ten to fourteen weeks. Multi-tenant SaaS booking platform:
    eighteen to twenty-eight weeks for a working v1, then ongoing as you onboard customers and
    learn what they actually need. We always ship a working build to TestFlight every two
    weeks so you can use it during development.
  </p>
</ServiceLayout>
